diff --git a/explanations.md b/explanations.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000..b5ec2219acb5dc2a7b6c06e250e2dfb3bc7b949c
--- /dev/null
+++ b/explanations.md
@@ -0,0 +1,127 @@
+# Generator Speedup: How the Two Changes Work
+
+## Before
+
+The old pipeline was:
+
+```
+go generate          → render templates (no imports)
+goimports --srcdir   → resolve + add imports (slow: runs Go type-checker on every file)
+gofumpt              → format
+goimports            → second pass to fix anything gofumpt broke
+go vet               → check
+```
+
+`goimports` was the bottleneck. It loads the full Go type-checker per file to figure out which packages are referenced, searches `GOPATH`/module cache for matching packages, and rewrites the import block. Doing this on 917 files took 30–60 seconds.
+
+## Change 1: Compute imports at generation time instead of after the fact
+
+### The problem
+
+The template rendered Go source with a hardcoded import block that only included `unsafe`, `structs`, `purego`, and `core` — the four packages the template always knew about. Cross-package references like `glib.Error`, `gobject.ConvertPtr`, or `gtk.Widget` were left unimported, requiring `goimports` to fix them up afterwards.
+
+### The solution
+
+An `ImportSet` type (`internal/gir/types/imports.go`) is threaded through every function that resolves GIR types into Go types. Each function records the imports it creates at the exact point where the cross-package reference is produced:
+
+- `AddAPI` in `template.go` — when it generates `glib.NewCallback(x)`, it calls `imps.AddV4("glib")`. When it generates `gobject.ConvertPtr(x)`, it calls `imps.AddV4("gobject")`. At the end, it calls `imps.TrackGoType(t)` on the final Go type, which scans for any `pkg.` prefix and records the corresponding `v4/pkg` import.
+
+- `AddThrows` in `template.go` — when a function has `throws="1"`, it appends `**glib.Error` to the pure arg types. If the current package isn't `glib`, it calls `imps.AddV4("glib")`.
+
+- `ReturnValue.Template` in `types.go` — after resolving the return type (which may be a class from another namespace like `*gtk.Widget`), it calls `imps.TrackGoType(val)` on the final API-visible type. If the return is a class with `transfer-ownership="none"`, it also records `gobject` (for `gobject.IncreaseRef`).
+
+- `Property.Template` in `types.go` — properties always need `gobject` (for `gobject.Value`). Boxed writable properties additionally need `glib` (for `glib.StrvGetType()` etc.), `unsafe`, and possibly `core`. Read-only boxed properties only need `core` and possibly `unsafe`. This distinction prevents unused imports on read-only boxed properties.
+
+- `ConvertInterface` in `interface.go` — when an interface from another namespace (e.g., `Gio.ActionMap` implemented by `Gtk.Application`) has methods that survive the `implemented` filter, it records the interface's namespace import (e.g., `imps.AddV4("gio")`). Only recorded when methods actually emit — if all methods were already implemented by the class, no import is added.
+
+- `writeGo` in `pass.go` — adds structural imports that the template always needs based on what the file contains: `structs` + `unsafe` for records (because of `structs.HostLayout` and `unsafe.Pointer` in `GoPointer()`), `purego` + `core` for files with an `init()` block, `purego` + `unsafe` + `glib` + `gobject` for files with signals. For callback fields on records, it adds `purego` + `unsafe` (for the `Override`/`Get` accessor wrappers). For callbacks as standalone types, it uses a throwaway `ImportSet` — callbacks only render `Pure.Types` and `Ret.Raw` in their type definition, so the API-level return type (which may reference a cross-package class) must not leak into the file's imports.
+
+- Enums/bitfields/aliases with a `TypeGetter` get `imps.AddTypes()` (for `gobject/types.GType`).
+
+The template's import block changed from hardcoded heuristics to:
+
+```
+{{if .Imports}}
+import (
+{{- range .Imports}}
+	"{{.}}"
+{{- end}}
+)
+{{end}}
+```
+
+The `TemplateArg.Imports` field (which already existed but was unused) is now populated with `pf.imps.Sorted()`.
+
+## Change 2: Format in-process with `go/format` instead of shelling out to `goimports`
+
+### The problem
+
+With imports now correct, `goimports` is no longer needed. But the raw template output still needs formatting — Go source without proper indentation and spacing.
+
+### The solution
+
+`go/format.Source` (from the stdlib `go/format` package) formats Go source in-process. Unlike `goimports`, it doesn't resolve imports or load the type-checker — it only parses and pretty-prints, which is very fast.
+
+The formatting is parallelized using `errgroup`:
+
+```go
+g2, _ := errgroup.WithContext(context.Background())
+for _, path := range allRaw {
+    g2.Go(func() error {
+        src, _ := os.ReadFile(path)
+        out, _ := format.Source(src)
+        return os.WriteFile(path, out, 0o644)
+    })
+}
+g2.Wait()
+```
+
+Template execution across repositories is also parallelized with a separate `errgroup`, collecting raw file paths into a shared slice under a mutex.
+
+## Change 3: Fix `throws` handling for functions with no other parameters
+
+### The problem
+
+Functions marked with `throws="1"` in the GIR (e.g., `g_async_result_legacy_propagate_error`) take a `GError**` output parameter. The generator was supposed to add `&cerr` to the call arguments and `**glib.Error` to the pure type signature. However, `Parameters.Template` in `types.go` had an early return when `p == nil` or `len(params) == 0` — it returned an empty `funcArgsTemplate{}` without checking `throws`. This meant any `throws="1"` function with zero regular parameters silently dropped the error argument.
+
+The generated Go code called these functions without the error pointer:
+
+```go
+cret := XGAsyncResultLegacyPropagateError(x.GoPointer())
+```
+
+The `cerr` variable was declared (by `Preamble`) and checked (by `Fmt`), but never actually passed to the C function — so errors were never propagated.
+
+### The fix
+
+Two early-return paths in `Parameters.Template` now check `throws` before returning empty:
+
+```go
+if p == nil {
+    if throws {
+        args := funcArgsTemplate{}
+        args.AddThrows(ns, imps)
+        return args
+    }
+    return funcArgsTemplate{}
+}
+// ...same for len(params) == 0
+```
+
+The generated code now correctly passes the error pointer:
+
+```go
+cret := XGAsyncResultLegacyPropagateError(x.GoPointer(), &cerr)
+```
+
+This affects `g_async_result_legacy_propagate_error`, `g_task_propagate_boolean`, `g_task_propagate_int`, `g_task_propagate_pointer`, `gdk_surface_create_gl_context`, `gdk_surface_create_vulkan_context`, `gtk_print_operation_get_error`, and `g_initable_init` — all `throws="1"` functions whose only parameter is the instance pointer.
+
+## Result
+
+| Step | Before | After |
+|------|--------|-------|
+| Template rendering | ~0.5s sequential | ~0.2s parallel across repos |
+| Import resolution | ~30–60s (`goimports` × 917 files) | 0s (computed during rendering) |
+| Formatting | ~5s (`gofumpt`) | ~0.7s (`go/format.Source` × 917 files, parallel) |
+| Second goimports pass | ~10s | eliminated |
+| **Total** | **~50–80s** | **~1.2s** |
